* Paired t-test for FEV1 data (again);

data fev;
  merge sasdata.fev_prepost(keep= subject test fev1_max where=(test="Post") rename=(fev1_max=fev1post))
        sasdata.fev_prepost(keep= subject test fev1_max where=(test="Pre") rename=(fev1_max=fev1pre));
    by subject;
  drop test;
run;
title 'FEV1 data: Posttest and Pretest measurements of (max) FEV1';
proc print data=fev;
run;
title 'Paired t-test for FEV1 data with PROC TTEST';
proc ttest data=fev;
  paired fev1pre*fev1post;
run;

* Two-sample t-test for pizza data;
title 'Reminder of what the pizza dataset looks like';
proc print data=sasdata.pizza(obs=10);
run;
title 'Two-sample t-test for pizza data with PROC TTEST';
proc ttest data=sasdata.pizza;
  class chain;
  var diameter_cm;
  label diameter_cm="Diameter (cm)";
run;
title 'Box plots of diameter for different pizza types';
proc sgplot data=sasdata.pizza;
  vbox diameter_cm/category=chain group=crust;
  label diameter_cm="Diameter (cm)";
run;
data pizza2;
  set sasdata.pizza;
  length crustclass $6;
  if crust in ("ThinNCrispy","ThinCrust") then crustclass="Thin";
  else if crust in ("ClassicCrust","MidCrust") then crustclass="Medium";
  else crustclass="Deep";
  label diameter_cm="Diameter (cm)";
run;
proc sort data=pizza2;
  by crustclass;
run;

ods trace on;
title 'Two-sample t-test for pizza data with PROC TTEST';
proc ttest data=pizza2;
  by crustclass;
  class chain;
  var diameter_cm;
run;

* Correlation Matrix for Life Expectancy and People per TVs/Doctors;

title 'Spearman correlations for variables in TVs dataset';
PROC CORR data=sasdata.tvs spearman fisher(alpha=0.10 type=twosided) plots=matrix(hist);
  var life_expect people_per_tv people_per_doc;
run;
 *Log transformation;
data tv2;
  set sasdata.tvs;
  logtv=log(people_per_tv);
  logdoc=log(people_per_doc);
run;
title 'Spearman correlations for variables in TVs dataset';
PROC CORR data=tv2 spearman plots=matrix(hist);
  var life_expect logtv logdoc;
run;

* Correlations among Body Measurements;

proc format;
  value sex 1="Male" 0="Female";
run;
data sasdata.body;
*  infile 'U:\Documents\courses\STAT 4-6360\Spring 15\Data Files\body.dat.txt';
  infile '/folders/myshortcuts/myFolders/Data Files/body.dat.txt';
  input biac_diam 1-4 biiliac_diam 6-9 bitroch_diam 11-14 chest_depth 16-19 chest_diam 21-24 elbow_diam 26-29
        wrist_diam 31-34 knee_diam 36-39 ankle_diam 41-44 should_girth 46-50 chest_girth 52-56 waist_girth 58-62
        navel_girth 64-68 hip_girth 70-74 thigh_girth 76-79 bicep_girth 81-84 forearm_girth 86-89 knee_girth 91-94
        calf_girth 96-99 ankle_girth 101-104 wrist_girth 106-109 age 111-114 weight 116-120 height 122-126 gender 128;
  format gender sex.;
  elbow_diam=elbow_diam/2;
  wrist_diam=wrist_diam/2;
  knee_diam=knee_diam/2;
  ankle_diam=ankle_diam/2;
  label
     biac_diam="Biacromial diameter"

     wrist_diam="Wrist diameter (mean)"
     knee_diam="Knee diameter (mean)"
     ankle_diam="Ankle diameter (mean)"

     chest_girth="Chest girth"

     gender="Gender"
     ;
run;
  
title 'Correlations among upper body (torso) measurements';
proc corr data=sasdata.body plots(maxpoints=none)=matrix plots=scatter(nvar=1 nwith=1 ellipse=prediction);
  var biac_diam--chest_diam; *skeletal measurements;
  with should_girth--hip_girth; * girth measurements;
run;

title 'Partial correlations among upper body (torso) measurements';
proc corr data=sasdata.body plots(maxpoints=none)=matrix;
  var biac_diam--chest_diam; *skeletal measurements;
  with should_girth--hip_girth; * girth measurements;
  partial age height gender; * for subjects of a given age, height, gender, how do the above variables correlate? ;
run;

* Car weight and mileage;

* First, consider a simple linear regression model;

title 'M1: Predicting city mpg from weight, 1993 Consumer Reports Cars data';
proc reg data=sasdata.cars simple;
  M1: model city_mpg=weight;
run;

proc standard data=sasdata.cars out=stdcars mean=0;
  var weight;
run;

data stdcars;
  set stdcars;
  wgt2=weight**2; * we will consider a quadratic model too, so we'll need this variable;
run;

title 'M1a: Predicting city mpg from weight, 1993 Consumer Reports Cars data';
title2 'Weight centered at its mean';
proc reg data=stdcars simple;
  M1a: model city_mpg=weight / clb;
run;

title 'M2: Predicting city mpg from weight, 1993 Consumer Reports Cars data';
title2 'Weight centered at its mean';
title3 'Quadratic model in weight';
proc reg data=stdcars simple plots=prediction(x=weight smooth);
  M2: model city_mpg=weight wgt2;
  label city_mpg ="City Mileage (mpg)" weight="Weight (centered & in lbs)" wgt2="Weight Squared";
run;

* Suppose I wanted to estimate the mean of Y at a different value of
  the explanatory variables than was contained in the dataset to which I fit the model.
  This can be done by adding an observation to the dataset that has the values of the
  explanatory variables that I am intereste in, but has a missing value
  for the response. Such an observation will not be used to fit the model because of the
  missing response, but fitted values will be generated for it.
  Below, we illustrate this by extrapolating (usually NOT a good idea) our
  fitted model to predict the mileage of a car that weighs 4300 lbs;
  * Note that we have to center 4300 lbs in the same way that weight was centered.
    Weight was centered by subtracting its mean, which was 3072.9, therefore 4300 becomes
    4500-3072.9=1427.1;

data newdata; * Here we predict just one new value, but could predict as many values as we want;
    weight=1427.1;
    wgt2=weight**2;
    city_mpg=.;
run;
data stdcars2;
  set newdata stdcars;
run;

title 'M2a: Predicting city mpg from weight, 1993 Consumer Reports Cars data';
title2 'Weight centered at its mean';
title3 'Quadratic model in weight';
proc reg data=stdcars2 simple plots=prediction(x=weight smooth);
  M2a: model city_mpg=weight wgt2/R;
  output out=regoutM2a p=yhat r=rawresid rstudent=exstudent student=intstudent lcl=lpl ucl=upl
    lclm=lcl uclm=ucl;
  label city_mpg ="City Mileage (mpg)" weight="Weight (centered & in lbs)" wgt2="Weight Squared";
run;
title;
* Below I illustrate how we can reproduce the fitted curve from the output dataset
  "by hand" (that is, by programming the steps ourselves). I will also add an
  identifier for the large outlier and extend the fitted curve to the prediction we made at
  the unobserved weight value of 4500 lbs (1427.1 after centering);

proc sort data=regoutm2a;
  by weight;
run;
data regoutm2a;
  set regoutm2a;
  if abs(exstudent)>4 then make_model=compress(manuf)||' '||model;
  else make_model='';
run;
title 'Dataset regoutM2a'; 
proc print data=regoutm2a(obs=10);
run;
title 'Fitted regression model and 95% CI and PI from model M2';
title2 'Including Prediction of mpg for 4500 lb car (extrapolation is bad!)';
proc sgplot data=regoutm2a;
  band x=weight lower=lpl upper=upl /
       legendlabel="95% PI for Y" name="band1";
  band x=weight lower=lcl upper=ucl / fillattrs=GraphConfidence2
       legendlabel="95% CI for Mean" name="band2";
  
  scatter x=weight y=city_mpg/datalabel=make_model;
  series x=weight y=yhat / lineattrs=GraphPrediction
         legendlabel="Predicted Fit" name="series";

  keylegend "series" "band1" "band2" / location=inside position=bottomright;
  label city_mpg ="City Mileage (mpg)" weight="Weight (centered & in lbs)";
run;
title2;

 *Pizza Diameters (Again);

data pizza3;
  set pizza2;
  if chain="Dominos" then pizzatype="Dom"||crustclass;
  else pizzatype="Eag"||crustclass;
  label pizzatype="Chain & Crust Type";
run;

title 'One-way anova model fit to pizza data with PROC ANOVA';
proc anova data=pizza3;
  class pizzatype;
  model diameter_cm=pizzatype;
  means pizzatype/hovtest=bf clm cldiff t tukey;
  * with no options, the above statement asks for means and SDs for each level of pizzatype. The hovtest=bf
    option asks for the Brown-Forsyth test of homogeneity of variance (equal variance in each treatment).
    The CLM option asks for confidence intervals for each mean and the CLDIFF asks for confidence intervals for 
    each pairwise difference between treatment means. The T option asks for those confidence intervals without any
    adjustment for multiplicity (no adjustment for the fact that we are doing several inferences here and that
    inflates the overall probability of making at least one type I error among all of the inferences we are conducting).
    The TUKEY option asks that the CLDIFF intervals also be computed with a multiplicity adjustment so that the
    probability that at least one interval fails to cover the quantity it is estimating is no greater than 0.05.
    The method for that multiplicity correction is Tukey's HSD method (there are many such methods available).;
run;

title 'One-way anova model fit to pizza data with PROC GLM';
proc glm data=pizza3;
  class pizzatype;
  model diameter_cm=pizzatype;
  lsmeans pizzatype/ cl pdiff=all adjust=tukey stderr ;
  * with no options, the above statement asks for means for each level of pizzatype. The CL option asks for CIs
    for each treatment mean. In the presence of PDIFF=all, CL also asks for CIs for each pairwise difference among treatment
    means. The ADJUST= option ask for the pairwise differences to be adjusted using (in this case) Tukey's HSD method, although
    other adjustment methods are available. In addition, there are other options for pdiff=. E.g., instead of asking for
    all pairwise differences, one can ask for all pairwise differences with the control treatment. For that choice
    (pdiff=control) a different adjustment method would be appropriate (adjust=Dunnett). The STDERR option asks for standard
    errors to be reported for each treatment mean. ;
  estimate 'Dom vs EB, Deep' intercept 0 pizzatype 1 0 0 -1 0 0;
  estimate 'Dom vs EB, Med' intercept 0 pizzatype 0 1 0 0 -1 0;
  estimate 'Dom vs EB, Thin' intercept 0 pizzatype 0 0 1 0 0 -1;
  estimate 'Dom vs EB, avged across all crusts' intercept 0 pizzatype 1 1 1 -1 -1 -1/divisor=3;
run;

data fake;
  call streaminit(19394); * set seed for rand num generator;
  sdx=1; sdy=2;
  do group=1 to 5;
    mux=5*group;    
    muy=10*group+10;
    do i=1 to 100;
      x=mux+rand('NORMAL',0,sdx); * generates x ~ N(mux,1^2) where mux=5, 10, 15, 20, 25 for groups 1-5, respectively.;
      y=muy+rand('NORMAL',0,sdy); * generates y ~ N(muy,2^2) where muy=20, 30, 40, 50, 60 for groups 1-5, respectively.;
      output;
    end;
  end;
run;

title 'Paneled scatter plot of y vs x for each group'; 
proc sgpanel data=fake;
  panelby group;
  scatter x=x y=y;
run;

title 'Scatter plot of y vs x, ignoring group';
proc sgplot data=fake;
  scatter x=x y=y;
run;

title 'Correlation between y and x';
proc corr data=fake;
  var x;
  with y;
run;

title 'Partial correlation between y and x controlling for group';
proc corr data=fake;
  var x;
  with y;
  ** add a PARTIAL statement here;
  partial group;
run;
